The Record Pattern: Indexing Shared Objects on Sui Without a Database
Building leafsheep.xyz (a DLMM liquidity manager on Sui), I hit a problem every Sui dev eventually hits:
How do you fetch all shared objects belonging to a user?
Owned objects are easy — GraphQL filters by owner and you're done. But shared objects don't have an owner field. And in DeFi, the most important user-facing objects are almost always shared.
Here's the pattern I ended up with. No off-chain database. No event indexer. Just Move + GraphQL.
📖 Full source code: https://github.com/RandyPen/cdpm
Why the obvious solutions fail
The PositionManager in leafsheep is a shared object holding a user's liquidity position, balances, and accrued fees. A user typically owns several of them across different pools and price ranges. The frontend needs all of them on page load.
Three "obvious" approaches, all broken:
1. Filter by owner via GraphQL. Doesn't work — shared objects have no owner.
2. Scan PositionManagerCreated events and filter client-side. Expensive (full historical scan, pagination), leaves stale state after objects are deleted (events are immutable), and pushes complex replay logic into the client.
3. Run an off-chain indexer + Postgres. Works, but throws away Sui's biggest advantage — that the chain itself is the source of truth. Now you've got two systems to keep in sync, and a database to operate.
So I built the index into the chain itself.
The design: two structs
rust
public struct GlobalRecord has key {
    id: UID,
    record: Table<address, ID>,
}

public struct Record has key {
    id: UID,
    record: Table<ID, bool>,
}

public struct PositionManager has key {
    id: UID,
    owner: address,
    agents: VecSet<address>,
    position: Option<Position>,
    balance: Bag,
    fee: Bag,
}
GlobalRecord — single shared object, maps address → Record ID. Used purely for deduplication.
Record — owned by the user. Internally a Table<ID, bool> listing every PositionManager they own. Table (not vector) for O(1) insert/remove and to avoid object size bloat.
PositionManager — the actual business object. Shared.
Registration: deduplication via abort semantics
rust
public fun register_and_return_record(
    global_record: &mut GlobalRecord,
    ctx: &mut TxContext,
): Record {
    let record = Record {
        id: object::new(ctx),
        record: table::new<ID, bool>(ctx),
    };
    let record_id = object::id(&record);
    table::add(&mut global_record.record, ctx.sender(), record_id);

    event::emit(RecordCreated { record_id, owner: ctx.sender() });
    record
}
Notice there's no contains check. Deduplication relies on table::add aborting when the key already exists. This is the cleanest way to enforce "one Record per address" in Move — a second registration call from the same address aborts the entire transaction. No conditional logic, no extra gas.
The function returns Record instead of transferring it, so a PTB can chain it directly into the first PositionManager creation in the same transaction.
Index writes: implicit permission via &mut Record
rust
public fun user_deposit_liquidity<CoinTypeA, CoinTypeB>(
    record: &mut Record,
    pool: &mut Pool<CoinTypeA, CoinTypeB>,
    // ...
) {
    // create position...

    let pm = PositionManager { /* ... */ };
    let pm_id = object::id(&pm);
    table::add(&mut record.record, pm_id, true);  // index write
    transfer::share_object(pm);

    event::emit(PositionManagerCreated { /* ... */ });
}
Because Record is owned, taking &mut Record as a parameter means only the Record's owner can call this function. No explicit access control needed — Sui's object model gives you authorization for free.
Deregistration: destroy_empty as a safety rail
rust
public fun unregister_record(
    global_record: &mut GlobalRecord,
    record: Record,
    ctx: &TxContext,
) {
    let Record { id, record } = record;
    record.destroy_empty();   // aborts if non-empty — intentional
    id.delete();
    let record_id = table::remove(&mut global_record.record, ctx.sender());

    event::emit(RecordDeleted { record_id, owner: ctx.sender() });
}
destroy_empty aborts if the table still has entries. This is intentional. It guarantees the index can never become a dangling reference — there is no possible state where a PositionManager exists on-chain but its owner's Record has been destroyed. Users must close every PositionManager (each removes itself from record.record) before they can deregister.
A tiny invariant, enforced by a one-line aborting primitive.
Frontend: walking the index with pure GraphQL
The full chain from wallet address to fully hydrated PositionManagers is three GraphQL hops. No backend, no DB.
Step 1 — address → Record ID
Record is owned, so a standard owner + type filter works. I run two equivalent queries in parallel and union the results, because GraphQL gateway implementations differ on which form they support:
typescript
query GetUserRecordIdsByAddress($owner: SuiAddress!, $recordType: String!) {
  address(address: $owner) {
    objects(first: 50, filter: { type: $recordType }) {
      nodes { address }
    }
  }
}

query GetUserRecordIdsByFilter($owner: SuiAddress!, $recordType: String!) {
  objects(first: 50, filter: { owner: $owner, type: $recordType }) {
    nodes { address }
  }
}
recordType is the fully qualified Move type: 0xbb15...8541::cdpm::Record.
Step 2 — Record → PM ID list
This is where most devs trip. A Sui Table doesn't store its entries inline — each entry is a dynamic field hanging off the Table's own UID. So we need two sub-steps:
2a. Read the Record object, extract the inner Table's UID:
typescript
query GetObjectJson($objectId: SuiAddress!) {
  object(address: $objectId) {
    asMoveObject {
      contents { json type { repr } }
    }
  }
}
contents.json.record.id is the Table UID.
2b. Page through dynamic fields under that UID. Every name.json is a PM ID:
typescript
query ListDynamicFields($parentId: SuiAddress!, $cursor: String) {
  address(address: $parentId) {
    dynamicFields(first: 50, after: $cursor) {
      pageInfo { hasNextPage endCursor }
      nodes {
        name { json }
        value {
          __typename
          ... on MoveValue  { json type { repr } }
          ... on MoveObject { contents { json type { repr } } }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
⚠️ The gotcha: in Sui's GraphQL schema, dynamicFields lives on the Address node, not the Object node. To list a Table's entries, treat the Table's UID as a SuiAddress and query address(address: tableUid).dynamicFields. Took me longer than I'd like to admit to figure out.
Step 3 — PM ID → details
Reuse GetObjectJson for each PM ID, in parallel.
The full path
markdown
walletAddress
  │
  │  GraphQL #1/#2  →  recordIds[]
  ▼
recordId
  │
  │  GraphQL #3 (read Record) → tableId
  │  GraphQL #4 (list dynamic fields, paginated) → pmIds[]
