  ▼
Hydrated UI
Three query types. Zero backend services. Chain is the source of truth, end to end.
When to use this pattern
Any object that is:
Shared (owned objects don't need this)
Belongs to a user, vault, or other entity
Needs to be enumerated by owner in a frontend
Lending positions, orderbook orders, marketplace listings, vault shares — all good fits.
Takeaways
Three things make this pattern punch above its weight:
No off-chain DB. The index is on-chain state. Nothing to operate, nothing to keep in sync, no eventual consistency to apologize for.
Authorization for free. &mut Record is the permission check. Move's object model does the work.
Invariants from abort primitives. table::add enforces uniqueness. destroy_empty enforces no-dangling-references. Two tiny aborts, one clean system.
The cost is one extra Table write on every create/destroy. For consumer DeFi, the trade is overwhelmingly worth it.
If you're building on Sui and finding yourself reaching for an indexer to solve a "list user's stuff" problem — try this first. The chain can do more than you think.
